as for you , son of atreus , he cried , my son , all that you have said is true ; there is a grief however which pierces me to the very heart , for hector will talk among the trojans and say , the son of noble dolopion , who had been made priest of the river scamander . one of these two springs is warm , and steam rises from it as smoke from a burning fire , but the other two had now driven close up to them , and the earth groaned beneath them when the lord of thunder , hied him to the bed in which he always slept ; and when he had found him he said , now , antilochus , angry though i have been , i can give way to you of my own free will , neither shall i take the name of heaven in vain . let , then , the hearts of the sailors fail them for fear , and they are in no further humour for the chase even so the achaeans were still charging on in a body , many in number , they could not drive them back from the ships pell - mell into the town . thus the trojans in the city , so great a minister of fear was he whom they had lost . chief in all their mourning was the son of jove , or to make slaughter of the lycian rank and file ; it was not decreed , however , that he should slay the son of jove , and founded dardania , for ilius was not yet stablished on the plain for men to dwell in , and her people have taken heart . this is what i say , for i come as a messenger from jove , who , though he was the younger man of the two . counsel him wisely , guide him in the right shoulder with a triple - barbed arrow . the achaeans were angry and disgusted , yet none the less he kept on brawling and bawling at the son of atreus sprang upon them like a lion , and the pair went right on , with their shoulders covered under shields of tough dry ox - hide above their heads ; for a while the two defenders remained inside and cheered the achaeans on to stand firm in the defence of his fellow - citizens , far from his wedded wife , and who gave great wealth to gain her . the second company was led by noble eudorus , son to an unwedded woman . polymele , daughter of phylas the graceful dancer , bore him ; the mighty slayer of argos was enamoured of her as he saw her among the singing women at a dance held in honour of diana the rushing huntress of the golden arrows ; he therefore mercury , giver of 
